---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="web-haptics Guide — changelogs.info" description="How to add tactile feedback to web apps with web-haptics, including Android vibrate API and iOS fallback strategy.">
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-10 sm:px-6">
    <a href="/resources" class="font-mono text-xs text-text-muted transition-colors hover:text-green"><span class="text-green">&lt;</span> back to /resources</a>

    <h1 class="mt-4 font-mono text-2xl font-bold text-green sm:text-3xl">
      <span class="text-green">/</span>guides/web-haptics
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-2 font-mono text-sm text-text-secondary">
      <span class="text-green">#</span> add tactile feedback to websites like native apps
    </p>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-lg border border-border bg-bg-card p-4">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">
        <span class="text-cyan">web-haptics</span> is an npm package for adding haptic feedback in web UIs.
        It works with React/Vue/Svelte/vanilla usage patterns and supports both presets and custom patterns.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="mt-8 font-mono text-base font-semibold text-green">quick start</h2>
    <pre class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border border-border bg-bg-card p-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">{`pnpm add web-haptics
# or npm i web-haptics`}</pre>

    <h2 class="mt-8 font-mono text-base font-semibold text-green">react-style usage</h2>
    <pre class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border border-border bg-bg-card p-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">{`import { useWebHaptics } from "web-haptics";

export function SaveButton() {
  const { trigger, cancel, isSupported } = useWebHaptics();

  return (
    <button
      onClick={() => trigger([{ delay: 0, duration: 15, intensity: 0.6 }])}
      onMouseLeave={cancel}
    >
      Save {isSupported ? "✓" : "(fallback)"}
    </button>
  );
}`}</pre>

    <h2 class="mt-8 font-mono text-base font-semibold text-green">custom vibration patterns</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 font-mono text-xs text-text-muted">Patterns are sequences of delay/duration/intensity. Example:</p>
    <pre class="mt-3 overflow-x-auto rounded border border-border bg-bg-card p-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">{`[
  { delay: 0, duration: 10, intensity: 0.4 },
  { delay: 70, duration: 20, intensity: 0.8 },
  { delay: 150, duration: 10, intensity: 0.5 }
]`}</pre>

    <h2 class="mt-8 font-mono text-base font-semibold text-green">ios support strategy</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">
      Android browsers usually support <code>navigator.vibrate()</code>. iOS does not expose this API reliably.
      A known workaround uses an invisible switch input toggle pattern to simulate tactile cues on iOS.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 font-mono text-base font-semibold text-green">good UX rules</h2>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">
      <li>• keep feedback subtle (5–20ms pulses for taps)</li>
      <li>• reserve stronger patterns for success/error confirmations</li>
      <li>• disable or reduce effects when <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> is set</li>
      <li>• never rely on haptics as the only success/error signal</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-8 rounded-lg border border-green/30 bg-green/[0.04] p-4">
      <p class="font-mono text-xs text-text-secondary">
        We use this style of haptic feedback on changelogs.info for taps on cards, filter buttons, and theme toggle actions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
